# =============================================================================
# WHITELIST .gitignore
# Deny everything by default, then explicitly allow only what should be
# committed to the repository.
# =============================================================================

# Deny all files and directories by default
*

# Re-allow directories (required so that we can selectively include files
# inside specific directories later)
!*/

# =============================================================================
# Explicitly allowed content (everything else stays ignored)
# =============================================================================

# --- Go source code and module files ---
!go.mod
!go.sum
!**/*.go

# --- Main application entrypoint ---
!cmd/
!cmd/**

# --- Internal packages ---
!internal/
!internal/**

# --- Docker & deployment ---
!Dockerfile
!docker-compose.yml
!docker-compose.*.yml

# --- GitHub Actions / CI configuration ---
!.github/
!.github/**

# --- Documentation and legal ---
!README.md
!LICENSE
!.env.example

# --- Web UI assets and templates (committed source) ---
!static/
!static/**
!templates/
!templates/**
!assets/
!assets/**

# --- Database migrations (if any) ---
!migrations/
!migrations/**

# --- The .gitignore file itself (good practice) ---
!.gitignore

# =============================================================================
# Notes:
# - Runtime data (storage/, *.db, tmp/, etc.) is automatically ignored
#   because we never explicitly allow it.
# - Binaries, build artifacts, IDE files, OS files, logs, etc. are ignored
#   by the initial `*` rule.
# - If you need to add something new to the repo, you must explicitly add
#   a `!path` rule above.
# =============================================================================
